Our main contributions can be summarised as follows:
1. We derive a set of asymptotically exact equations that describe the generalisation dynamics of shallow, nonlinear autoencoders trained using online stochastic gradient descent (SGD) (section 3.1);
2. Using these equations, we show how autoencoders learn important features of their data sequentially (3.2); we analyse the long-time dynamics of learning and highlight the importance of untying the weights of decoder and encoder (3.3); and we show that training the biases is necessary for Re LU autoencoders; (3.4)
3. We illustrate how a modiﬁcation of vanilla SGD breaking the rotational symmetry of neurons yields the exact principal components of the data (section 3.5);
4. We ﬁnally show that the equations also capture the learning dynamics of non-linear autoencoders trained on more realistic datasets such as CIFAR10 with great accuracy, and discuss connections with recent results on Gaussian universality in neural network models in section 4.
